    <centralBlocks>
      <Value><![CDATA[[
  {
    "key": "f736d4e7-d1a9-46ca-8788-ac62e7a26b21",
    "name": "Scanned images",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "Scanned images",
    "content": "<div class=\"page\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p>Scanned images are often very large and can take up a considerable amount of space. To minimise this, you should save your scan as a .jpg file, if possible. Do not save the file as a .pdf file. Once the file is saved, follow the instructions below for standalone images to minimise the file size.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>"
  },
  {
    "key": "c94feada-e512-4f06-ae51-6350066c7044",
    "name": "Standalone images",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "Standalone images",
    "content": "<div class=\"page\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p>One of the key contributors to a large file size is the resolution - the size of the image on screen. Generally, any image that takes up more than your screen should be reduced. It is easy to do this using Paint as shown below.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>"
  },
  {
    "key": "a4071bb5-4d5f-4718-8eb9-45e1eb3ade7a",
    "name": "Opening an image file",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "Opening an image file",
    "content": "<div class=\"page\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p>To open a file, locate it by navigating to the folder where it is saved. Once you have located the file, right click on the icon and select Open with... &gt; Paint</p>\n<p>[image of paint]</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>"
  },
  {
    "key": "f16eef59-254b-4469-89a1-7a20de3f3034",
    "name": "Cropping the image",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "Cropping the image",
    "content": "<div class=\"page\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p>Sometimes, it is not necessary to use the whole image in your document. In these instances, it is possible to <strong>crop</strong> your image and discard the parts you no longer require. Cropping an image also helps to reduce file size.</p>\n<div class=\"page\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<ul>\n<li>Once the paint window opens up press the Esc key and click on the Select tool</li>\n</ul>\n<p>[image of paint tools]</p>\n<div class=\"page\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<ul>\n<li>To select a specific part of the window, drag your mouse, while holding the left mouse button, across the area you want to select. The area will be highlighted with a broken line as shown to the right:</li>\n</ul>\n<p>[image of paint tools]</p>\n<div class=\"page\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<ul>\n<li>Copy the selected area to your clipboard by pressing Ctrl+C</li>\n</ul>\n<p>[image of paint tools]</p>\n<div class=\"page\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p>You must now open up a new Paint document before you can save it. Using the File &gt; New option from within paint will close the image you are working with</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Open up Paint from the Start menu:</li>\n</ul>\n<p>[image of windows UI]</p>\n<div class=\"page\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<ul>\n<li>Paste the cropped image into paint by pressing Ctrl+V</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"page\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p><strong>Resizing the image</strong></p>\n<div class=\"page\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p>Typically, files where the whole image can be viewed on your screen will be of a reasonable size.</p>\n<p>Once the image has opened, you will be able to see if it fits the screen or not. If you do not see the whole image, you should resize it before saving the file. Unfortunately, due to the resizing process, there may be a loss of image quality. The effects of this can vary; however, it is normally only noticeable when you resize an image that is smaller than your screen. This is why cropping your image appropriately is important.</p>\n<p>[image of paint tools]</p>\n<div class=\"page\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<ul>\n<li>Press the Esc key on your keyboard, this ‘deselects’ the image and ensures that the whole image is resized properly</li>\n<li>From the Menu bar at the top of the window, click on Image &gt; Stretch/skew</li>\n</ul>\n<p>[image of paint tools]</p>\n<div class=\"page\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p>A new window will pop up which will allow you to resize your image. Ensure that you adjust both the horizontal and vertical values at the same time to maintain the image proportions</p>\n<p>Once you have reduced the image to a suitable size, save the newly edited image.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>"
  },
  {
    "key": "dff3c88b-6aa9-4a4c-ae19-f0dbf1dceef0",
    "name": "Saving the image as a new file",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "Saving the image as a new file",
    "content": "<p>It is important that you save your file in a suitable which ensures a reduced file size, and the ability for almost anyone to be able to view the file if they are given access. Generally, the .jpg format is most common and easily handled.</p>\n<p>[image of paint tools]</p>\n<ul>\n<li>From the Menu bar, select File &gt; Save As this will open up a new window where you will be able to change the file format and also decide where to save it</li>\n<li>In the Save as window, navigate to where you want to save the file</li>\n</ul>\n<p>[image of paint tools]</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Enter a name for the image you want to save</li>\n<li>Select .JPEG as the file format</li>\n<li>Click on Save.</li>\n</ul>"
  },
  {
    "key": "388ec411-e070-4d5d-a612-751ce7aa76e2",
    "name": "Image files in Office documents",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "Image files in Office documents",
    "content": "<p>Now that you have edited your image, you may want to put it into a document such as a PowerPoint presentation, or a Word document. Below are instructions on how to do this, and also how to ensure that the document is as compressed as possible.</p>\n<p>The instructions make reference to Microsoft Word 2007, however, the principles can be transferred to PowerPoint, Excel etc. very easily.</p>\n<p><strong>Insert an image</strong></p>\n<p>Click on the Insert Tab at the top of your Word document and then select the Picture button.</p>\n<p>[image of paint tools]</p>\n<p>Using the Insert Picture window that pops up, navigate to the image you want to insert then click on the Insert button</p>\n<p>[image of paint tools]</p>\n<p>The selected image will now be appear in your document:</p>\n<p>[image of cropped image]</p>\n<p>Saving the Office document:</p>\n<p>It is important to save the document so that it is as small as possible. To do this:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Click on the Office button at the top left corner of the window and select Save As &gt; Word document</li>\n</ul>\n<p>[image of windows UI]</p>\n<ul>\n<li>When the Save As window appears click on the Tools button and select Compress Pictures</li>\n</ul>\n<p>[image of windows UI]</p>\n<ul>\n<li>From the box that appears click on Options</li>\n</ul>\n<p>[image of options box]</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The below image shows the three different options:</li>\n</ul>\n<p>[image of options box]</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Select the option that best suits the purpose for which your document is being created</li>\n<li>Click onÂ <strong>OK</strong>Â for both boxes and thenÂ <strong>Save</strong> your document ensuring the <strong>Save as type</strong> option</li>\n<li>is set toÂ <strong>Word document (*.docx).</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p> </p>"
  },
  {
    "key": "0fcda30e-1580-4adf-a56f-dfe0fa1bdf19",
    "name": "Saving the Office document:",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "Saving the Office document:",
    "content": "<div class=\"page\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p>It is important to save the document so that it is as small as possible. To do this:</p>\n<div class=\"page\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<ul>\n<li>Click on the <strong>Office</strong> button at the top left corner of the window and select <strong>Save As &gt; Word document</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>[image of windows UI]</p>\n<div class=\"page\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<ul>\n<li>When the <strong>Save As</strong> window appears click on the <strong>Tools</strong> button and select <strong>Compress Pictures</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>[image of windows UI]</p>\n<div class=\"page\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<ul>\n<li>From the box that appears click on <strong>Options</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>[image of windows UI]</p>\n<div class=\"page\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p>The below image shows the three different options</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>[image of windows UI]</p>\n<div class=\"page\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<ul>\n<li>Select the option that best suits the purpose for which your document is being created</li>\n<li>Click on <strong>OK</strong> for both boxes and then Save your document ensuring the <strong>Save as type</strong> option is set to <strong>Word document (*.docx)</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p> </p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>"
  },
  {
    "key": "0c55fdba-ca0f-47ec-9b2c-0796777cfa6b",
    "name": "Saving your Office Document as a .pdf file",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "Saving your Office Document as a .pdf file",
    "content": "<div class=\"page\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p>A feature introduced in Office 2007 is that users can save their documents as a .pdf file. There are two key advantages of saving documents as .pdf files.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Converting to .pdf provides further compression of the document over the Office document compression</li>\n<li>pdf makes files a lot more secure as recipients of the documents are not easily able to edit them. To do this, specialist software is required (Adobe X Standard).</li>\n</ol>\n<p>To save your document as a .pdf file:</p>\n<div class=\"page\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<ul>\n<li>Click on the Office button at the top left corner of the window and select Save As &gt; PDF or XPS</li>\n</ul>\n<p>[image of windows UI]</p>\n<div class=\"page\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<ul>\n<li>When the following window appears, navigate to where you want to save your file</li>\n</ul>\n<p>[image of windows UI]</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"page\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<div class=\"page\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<ul>\n<li>Select the optimisation option that suits the purpose for which your document will be used:</li>\n<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\n<ul>\n<li>Standard (publishing online and printing)</li>\n<li>Minimum size (publishing online)</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Click on Publish.</li>\n</ul>\n<p> </p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>"
  },
  {
    "key": "a3e7a679-c2ee-4abc-b8f7-a02cc7dd66c8",
    "name": "Item 9",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "APPENDIX",
    "content": "<div class=\"page\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p><span class=\"lead\">Screenshots</span></p>\n<p>A screenshot is an image which gives an instant capture of what is visible on your computer screen at any given time. The files generated can be large, so it is important to reduce the size of the files where possible – especially if you plan to import the image files into any web-based applications, such as ePortfolio or Wiki. This guide will take you through the process of taking a screenshot and ensuring that it is suitable for uploading.</p>\n<div class=\"page\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p><strong>Taking the screenshot:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>When you have the item on screen you wish to capture press the <strong>PRINT SCREEN</strong> – <strong>SysRq key</strong>, typically just above the Backspace key.</li>\n<li>You now have the screen ‘captured’</li>\n</ul>\n<p>[Keyboard Image]</p>\n<div class=\"page\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p><strong>Editing the screenshot:</strong></p>\n<p>As a screenshot is just an image of your screen and can be edited like any other image in Paint. To put the screenshot into<strong> Paint:</strong></p>\n<p>Open up <strong>Paint</strong> from the <strong>Start</strong> menu</p>\n<p>[image of windows UI]</p>\n<div class=\"page\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p>Paste the screenshot into paint by pressing Ctrl+V</p>\n<p>[Keyboard Image]</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>"
  }
]]]></Value>
